{
  "text": "It is well known that the social determinants of health play a momentous role in chronic disease risk. Life expectancy is shorter and most diseases, including cardiovascular disease, are more common further down the social ladder (Institute of Medicine (US) 2010; Wilkinson & Marmot, 2003) , where people may have lower income, poor or less education, and disadvantageous circumstances. Adults with lower levels of education are significantly more likely to develop heart disease than those with higher levels of education [CITATION_1] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
